node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 05, 2021. May be an image of elephant and nature.

node.text:
Photo by @amivitale / Shaba, an orphaned elephant herself, became the proxy matriarch of the herd of younger orphaned elephants at Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) in northern Kenya. Under the eye of caretakers, she would lead her small herd into the bush, teaching them how to browse and be wild. Elephants are ecosystem “engineers” that feed on low brush and bulldoze small trees, promoting growth of grasses. This in turn attracts bulk grazers like buffalo, endangered Grevy’s zebras, eland, and oryx, which are prey for carnivores lions, cheetahs, wild dogs, and leopards.
Follow @amivitale and @r.e.s.c.u.e to learn more, including how you can help. @kenyawildlifeservice @thephotosociety #protectelephants #elephants #stoppoaching #kenya #empathyiseverything

node.text: Photo by Muhammed Muheisen @mmuheisen / The Temple of Hercules is a historic site in the Amman Citadel in Jordan. For more photos and videos from different parts of the world, follow me @mmuheisen and @mmuheisenpublic. #muhammedmuheisen #Amman #الاردن #Citadel

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 04, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Photo by @jodymacdonaldphoto / Sossusvlei, Namibia, is a desert of incomparable beauty. As a photographer, I can't seem to get enough of this magical place. It is home to some of the highest and oldest dunes in the world, but what really makes it spectacular is the sand's rich, vivid orange color. The color is the result of a high concentration of oxidized iron built up over time, making these dunes mesmerizing to look at. 
Follow me @jodymacdonaldphoto to see more images from my travels around the world. #Namibia #Africa #Travel

node.text: Photo by @dina_litovsky / This summer New York City has been slowly coming alive again. With more than 70 percent of adults vaccinated, most mask mandates have been removed. It’s a joy to see the city reviving and regaining its former energy. For more images, follow me @dina_litovsky.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 04, 2021. May be an image of tree, body of water and nature.

node.text: Photo by @stephen_matera / Fall colors reflect in a subalpine pond in Uncompahgre National Forest, Colorado. Late September and early October bring a blaze of color to the mountains of southern Colorado. Follow me @stephen_matera for more images like this from Colorado and around the world. #Autumn #Aspen #UncompahgreNationalForest

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 04, 2021. May be an image of goose and nature.

node.text: Photo by @kiliiiyuyan / Greater white-fronted geese shift positions within their migratory V-formation at Teshekpuk Lake in Alaska. Teshekpuk Lake, in the Arctic, is one of the most important regions in the world for migratory birds, within the poorly named National Petroleum Reserve. On this day in early June, millions of birds were flying in from the south to find nesting locations here. #arctic #alaska #teshekpuk

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 03, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / During the 2019 Greenland Caves Project expedition, the main reason for moving to Camp 2 was to visit Grotte de Quatre (pictured), which was discovered in the 1980s during an expedition by a French team. For a cave in Greenland, it is quite complex. It has multiple entrances and several passages. We wanted to investigate it to look for calcite, but unfortunately we didn’t find any.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 03, 2021. May be an image of standing and nature.

node.text:
Photo by @daisygilardini / King penguins court on the sheep pasture of Volunteer Point in the Falkland Islands (Islas Malvinas). Seeing these penguins court is quite a show. To attract a partner, a male performs an ecstatic display, which includes trumpeting calls while stretching his neck as far as it will go. If the female is responsive, the two will engage in a mutual display of stretching, cooing, bowing, and bobbing heads.
Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #wildlifephotography #penguin #kingpenguin #climatechange #conservation

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 03, 2021. May be an image of nature and body of water.

node.text: Photo by @juancristobalcobo / Fishermen start their daily routine on the Nechí River early in the morning. The river is also known as the Gold River because of its significant gold deposits. Located in northwestern Colombia, it flows into the Cauca River. #nechí #colombia #fishing #juancristobalcobo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 03, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, sky and skyscraper.

node.text: Photo by @MichaelGeorge / Visitors at the Edge NYC look at the city more than 1,100 feet (336 meters) below. This corner is not for the faint of heart, as it floats freely above the Hudson Yards neighborhood of Manhattan. The views—of Central Park, downtown, all three bridges to Brooklyn, and even New Jersey—are worth the slight vertigo. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #edgenyc #hudsonyards #nyc #newyorkcity #Manhattan

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 03, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text: Photo by @krystlejwright / Visitors lie like lizards in the sun at Fortescue Falls in Karijini National Park. While traveling through the park in the winter, the temperatures can still create days that feel like summer. Winter is the prime time to venture through the desert of Western Australia, as the summer brings the soaring heat and the wet season, which often makes many places inaccessible.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 02, 2021. May be an image of nature and mountain.

node.text:
Photo by @amivitale / Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) keepers take Shaba and Pokot to walk in the Namunyak Wildlife Conservancy in northern Kenya. Rescued as young calves, Shaba and Pokot were cared for by the dedicated team at Reteti until they were ready to return to the wild. The elephants were transferred to nearby Sera Conservancy for their soft release back to the wild on November 16, 2019.
Follow @amivitale for more extraordinary stories of people and wildlife coexisting. @kenyawildlifeservice @thephotosociety #protectelephants #elephants #stoppoaching #kenya #empathyiseverything
